501
00:29:27,899 --> 00:29:29,799
(all laugh)

502
00:29:29,834 --> 00:29:32,667
No, but seriously,
I mean, the thing is...

503
00:29:43,148 --> 00:29:45,412
Excuse... sorry.

504
00:29:51,656 --> 00:29:53,283
(breathes deeply)

505
00:30:25,590 --> 00:30:28,286
Harvey: Right here's good, friend.
Thanks. I want to walk.

506
00:30:30,028 --> 00:30:33,293
Excuse me, could you take me
to Wilton Green?

507
00:30:42,907 --> 00:30:48,812
By the powers vested in me,
I now pronounce you husband and wife.

508
00:30:48,847 --> 00:30:53,978
You may kiss the bride.

509
00:31:29,420 --> 00:31:31,012
To Heathrow.

510
00:31:33,591 --> 00:31:35,149
Spirits?
Champagne?

511
00:31:36,194 --> 00:31:38,856
Okay. Excellent.

512
00:31:44,235 --> 00:31:46,169
(horns honking)

513
00:31:50,475 --> 00:31:52,443
Can we go another way?

514
00:31:52,477 --> 00:31:54,206
You're having a laugh,
ain't you?

515
00:31:54,245 --> 00:31:55,644
It'll be bad everywhere.

516
00:32:03,187 --> 00:32:05,678
(both arguing)

517
00:32:15,867 --> 00:32:17,858
Sorry.

518
00:32:17,902 --> 00:32:20,894
I'm sorry.
I have the 1:30 to JFK.

519
00:32:20,939 --> 00:32:22,566
I'm sorry, Sir.
I'm dealing with a passenger.

520
00:32:22,607 --> 00:32:25,041
- I want to go straight to the gate.
- I will answer all your questions,

521
00:32:25,076 --> 00:32:28,102
- but you will have to wait.
- Okay. Ma'am, excuse me.

522
00:32:28,146 --> 00:32:30,273
- I'm on the 1:30 flight to JFK.
- Sir... Sir, there is a queue.

523
00:32:30,315 --> 00:32:32,783
I appreciate that,
but I'm on the 1:30 flight to JFK.

524
00:32:32,817 --> 00:32:34,250
That flight's now closed.

525
00:32:34,285 --> 00:32:36,116
No no no, the plane
doesn't take off for 40 minutes.

526
00:32:36,154 --> 00:32:37,985
Sir, the gate
is already closed.

527
00:32:38,022 --> 00:32:40,115
But all I have is hand luggage.
Please, just let me through.

528
00:32:40,158 --> 00:32:42,422
- Sir, that is not hand luggage.
- What, this?

529
00:32:42,460 --> 00:32:46,453
- Now will you let me on, please?
- No, Sir.

530
00:32:46,497 --> 00:32:47,862
When's the next flight?

531
00:32:47,899 --> 00:32:50,163
(sighs)

532
00:32:50,201 --> 00:32:52,726
The earliest I can get you on for sure is
tomorrow morning.

533
00:32:52,770 --> 00:32:55,204
- Tomorrow?!
- Sir, you're gonna have to stay calm.

534
00:32:55,239 --> 00:32:58,800
Marvin, it's Harvey.
Listen, the traffic was crazy.

535
00:32:58,843 --> 00:33:00,572
I'm gonna have to reschedule slightly.

536
00:33:00,611 --> 00:33:02,340
Come on, Harvey.
The traffic?

537
00:33:02,380 --> 00:33:04,143
- Jesus. Come on.
- Frank can set up.

538
00:33:04,182 --> 00:33:05,649
I'll e-mail them
the queue numbers,

539
00:33:05,683 --> 00:33:07,514
and then I'll be there at lunchtime
at the latest.

540
00:33:07,552 --> 00:33:09,383
I'll come straight
from the airport.

541
00:33:09,420 --> 00:33:12,617
Look, just stay in London, will you? Just
enjoy your daughter's wedding.

542
00:33:12,657 --> 00:33:13,749
No no, Marvin, it's fine.

543
00:33:13,791 --> 00:33:15,452
- There's no problem.
- Harvey.

544
00:33:15,493 --> 00:33:19,361
Frank knows exactly what to do, and Mike
is gonna be right there to help.

545
00:33:19,397 --> 00:33:22,560
- Harvey, we've got to talk.
No no no. No, listen.

546
00:33:22,600 --> 00:33:26,366
I'll be there at lunchtime, Marvin.
It's okay. It's all set up.

547
00:33:26,404 --> 00:33:28,099
- Harvey?
- Yeah? What?

548
00:33:28,139 --> 00:33:30,937
- It's over.
- What?

549
00:33:30,975 --> 00:33:32,704
- What do you mean?
- It's out of my hands.

550
00:33:32,744 --> 00:33:36,612
There's people I got to answer to.
I'm letting you go.

551
00:33:36,647 --> 00:33:40,515
We'll talk
when you get back.

552
00:33:55,767 --> 00:33:57,200
Hi.

553
00:33:57,235 --> 00:33:59,226
Can I have a Johnnie Walker,

554
00:33:59,270 --> 00:34:01,363
and if you have a black label,
neat?

555
00:34:09,080 --> 00:34:11,048
Thanks.

556
00:34:15,520 --> 00:34:17,317
Another, please.

557
00:34:19,857 --> 00:34:21,916
It's okay.
Thank you.

558
00:34:27,832 --> 00:34:30,733
- Aw, shit!
- (woman murmurs)

559
00:34:30,768 --> 00:34:33,293
Sorry.
Vulgar American.

560
00:34:45,049 --> 00:34:46,710
How you doing?

561
00:34:49,053 --> 00:34:50,418
I'm sorry, by the way.

562
00:34:50,455 --> 00:34:53,356
For what?

563
00:34:53,391 --> 00:34:55,757
Weren't you the gal who tried to
ask me some questions,

564
00:34:55,793 --> 00:34:58,284
and you were just doing your job,
and I was rude?

565
00:34:58,329 --> 00:35:00,763
I'm sorry.

566
00:35:00,798 --> 00:35:05,292
I don't remember, really,
but you probably were.

567
00:35:05,336 --> 00:35:07,861
Most people are.

568
00:35:07,905 --> 00:35:10,897
Hmm.

569
00:35:10,942 --> 00:35:12,705
Good book?

570
00:35:12,743 --> 00:35:14,938
Would be
if I could finish it.

571
00:35:14,979 --> 00:35:16,537
Ooh!

572
00:35:17,915 --> 00:35:21,009
(laughs)

573
00:35:23,588 --> 00:35:25,579
- That'll help.
- What?

574
00:35:25,623 --> 00:35:27,454
I said, "That'll help."

575
00:35:27,492 --> 00:35:29,426
- What? This?
- Mm.

576
00:35:29,460 --> 00:35:31,451
Oh, yes it will,
and it is.

577
00:35:31,496 --> 00:35:33,361
Right.

578
00:35:35,199 --> 00:35:39,397
It'll help as much as that trashy novel and a
glass of Chardonnay.

579
00:35:39,437 --> 00:35:41,667
(sighs)

580
00:35:48,880 --> 00:35:50,609
Sorry.

581
00:35:50,648 --> 00:35:52,809
I'm sorry.

582
00:35:55,486 --> 00:35:56,748
I'm sorry.
That was out of line.

583
00:35:56,787 --> 00:35:59,551
Go away!
Stop apologizing.

584
00:35:59,590 --> 00:36:02,058
It's just that I've had
a really shitty day.

585
00:36:02,093 --> 00:36:03,424
Join the club.

586
00:36:03,461 --> 00:36:06,828
Oh no, yours may have been shitty,
but mine was shittier.

587
00:36:06,864 --> 00:36:10,527
Mine was major shitty, you know?
Huh?

588
00:36:15,106 --> 00:36:16,437
How shitty?

589
00:36:21,179 --> 00:36:24,046
I missed the plane, I
lost my job,

590
00:36:24,081 --> 00:36:26,208
and my daughter,
who's getting married today,

591
00:36:26,250 --> 00:36:31,984
decided that she wanted her stepfather
rather than me to give her away, okay?

592
00:36:32,023 --> 00:36:33,957
And that took it
to major shitty.

593
00:36:37,094 --> 00:36:39,358
Fair enough.
You win.

594
00:36:42,667 --> 00:36:45,659
What do you say,
let me make it up to both of us,

595
00:36:45,703 --> 00:36:47,500
and I'll buy you lunch?

596
00:36:48,773 --> 00:36:51,367
Or tea. How about tea,
if it's teatime?

597
00:36:51,409 --> 00:36:55,175
Thanks very much, but I don't know you,
and you don't know me, so...

598
00:36:55,213 --> 00:36:57,704
That's exactly why
we should have tea together.

599
00:36:57,748 --> 00:37:00,512
It's very sweet of you,
but thank you. No.

600
00:37:02,553 --> 00:37:04,851
- Well, you've got your book.
- Mm.

601
00:37:07,058 --> 00:37:08,889
(cellphone ringing)

602
00:37:08,926 --> 00:37:12,054
If that's for me,
I'm in the shower.

603
00:37:17,535 --> 00:37:20,163
Aren't you gonna answer it?

604
00:37:20,204 --> 00:37:23,002
No.

605
00:37:25,509 --> 00:37:28,410
Should I take that
as a hopeful sign?

606
00:37:28,446 --> 00:37:33,179
If it is, you can give me
a little wider smile.

607
00:37:35,653 --> 00:37:38,622
(sighs)

608
00:38:01,379 --> 00:38:02,744
Thank you.

609
00:38:02,780 --> 00:38:05,044
See?

610
00:38:05,082 --> 00:38:06,709
We're having lunch together.

611
00:38:06,751 --> 00:38:08,912
No, we're having lunch
next to each other.

612
00:38:08,953 --> 00:38:11,080
Ah.

613
00:38:11,122 --> 00:38:14,523
By the way,
Harvey... Harvey Shine.

614
00:38:16,894 --> 00:38:18,361
Kate Walker.

615
00:38:18,396 --> 00:38:19,954
So, why aren't you
at the wedding?

616
00:38:19,997 --> 00:38:21,362
(vacuum whirring)

617
00:38:22,767 --> 00:38:26,203
I knew there was something
that was missing.

618
00:38:26,237 --> 00:38:28,398
I had to get back for work.

619
00:38:28,439 --> 00:38:29,770
What, for the job
you just lost?

620
00:38:29,807 --> 00:38:32,867
(chuckles)
Yes, exactly.

621
00:38:32,910 --> 00:38:37,210
Did you enjoy it,
the job?

622
00:38:37,248 --> 00:38:39,148
Yes. No.

623
00:38:39,183 --> 00:38:40,912
Yes, originally.

624
00:38:40,951 --> 00:38:42,077
What was it?

625
00:38:43,854 --> 00:38:45,151
I write jingles.

626
00:38:47,124 --> 00:38:50,059
- Wow.
- That's a normal response.

627
00:38:50,094 --> 00:38:53,723
(chuckles) Did you always want to write
jingles, or was...

628
00:38:53,764 --> 00:38:56,062
was there something more?

629
00:38:56,100 --> 00:38:58,227
(laughs)

630
00:38:58,269 --> 00:38:59,531
What?

631
00:38:59,570 --> 00:39:01,504
No no, I love it.

632
00:39:01,539 --> 00:39:04,804
You cut right through it.
I like that.

633
00:39:04,842 --> 00:39:08,107
- I'll take that as a compliment.
- You should.

634
00:39:11,849 --> 00:39:15,945
I would have given anything...

635
00:39:15,986 --> 00:39:18,113
to have been a jazz pianist.

636
00:39:18,155 --> 00:39:21,147
Were you good?

637
00:39:24,395 --> 00:39:25,794
No. Not good enough.

638
00:39:28,232 --> 00:39:32,965
Sorry.
I... can be a bit nosy.

639
00:39:34,271 --> 00:39:37,138
Yeah, and I like it.

640
00:39:37,174 --> 00:39:39,267
- Do you believe me?
- Mm.

641
00:39:42,213 --> 00:39:45,842
I have to tell you that
is a relief to find someone

642
00:39:45,883 --> 00:39:49,751
who actually says what they're feeling and
what they're thinking.

643
00:39:49,787 --> 00:39:53,018
Especially in a place
that's supposed to be...

644
00:39:53,057 --> 00:39:57,221
you know...
Britain, English, reserved.

645
00:39:57,261 --> 00:40:00,389
Oh, no no. Haven't you heard?
We're a nation changed.

646
00:40:00,431 --> 00:40:04,800
Ever since Diana died, we're all sort of
flowing out of us like water.

647
00:40:04,835 --> 00:40:07,303
You guys showed us the way,
actually.

648
00:40:07,338 --> 00:40:09,067
No more
stiff upper lip for us.

649
00:40:09,106 --> 00:40:10,573
And what is that, exactly?

650
00:40:10,608 --> 00:40:12,473
- What?
- "Stiff upper lip."

651
00:40:14,812 --> 00:40:16,712
I'm not sure,
it's kind of...

652
00:40:18,249 --> 00:40:19,739
that whole clenched thing.

653
00:40:19,784 --> 00:40:22,082
- Clenched?
- I think so, you know.

654
00:40:22,119 --> 00:40:25,054
See, when you cry,
your lips wobble,

655
00:40:25,089 --> 00:40:27,080
and when you're being strong,
they don't.

656
00:40:27,124 --> 00:40:29,752
Like this.

657
00:40:29,794 --> 00:40:32,262
No, that's sort of
more like a bulldog.

658
00:40:32,296 --> 00:40:35,891
No, don't do that. You look like
you've got no teeth at all.

659
00:40:35,933 --> 00:40:39,562
It's my first attempt
at a stiff upper lip.

660
00:40:39,603 --> 00:40:41,002
- Who does...
- I don't really kn...

661
00:40:41,038 --> 00:40:42,972
I think it's the sort of tension
in your jaw.

662
00:40:43,007 --> 00:40:44,338
Who does that?

663
00:40:44,375 --> 00:40:46,070
- Aristocrats.
- The aristocrats?

664
00:40:46,110 --> 00:40:47,737
Posh people.

665
00:40:55,319 --> 00:40:57,947
- Thank you. I enjoyed that.
- Me too. Where are you going?

666
00:40:57,988 --> 00:41:00,980
- I'm just going to a class, actually.
- What kind of class?

667
00:41:01,025 --> 00:41:02,390
- Writing.
- Ah.

668
00:41:02,426 --> 00:41:04,758
It's just a thing,
twice a week, I do.

669
00:41:04,795 --> 00:41:07,127
I've got to get the Heathrow Express,
actually, so...

670
00:41:07,164 --> 00:41:08,791
- I see.
- What about you?

671
00:41:08,833 --> 00:41:11,961
I don't know. I guess I'll stay
in a hotel near here.

672
00:41:12,002 --> 00:41:14,061
- I have a flight in the morning.
- Oh, so it's... yeah.

673
00:41:14,104 --> 00:41:15,935
- Okay.
- Bye-bye, then.

674
00:41:15,973 --> 00:41:17,235
- Bye.
- Good luck.

675
00:41:17,274 --> 00:41:19,174
- (cellphone ringing)
- There's your phone again.

676
00:41:19,210 --> 00:41:20,199
(both chuckle)

677
00:41:24,482 --> 00:41:26,143
Hello?

678
00:41:26,183 --> 00:41:27,775
Yes.

679
00:42:04,955 --> 00:42:07,048
Harvey: Sorry. I'm sorry.

680
00:42:08,192 --> 00:42:09,250
Sorry.

681
00:42:14,999 --> 00:42:17,263
Hi.

682
00:42:17,301 --> 00:42:18,598
Sorry.

683
00:42:18,636 --> 00:42:21,298
The thought of staying at a hotel
near the runway unnerved me.

684
00:42:21,338 --> 00:42:23,306
(chuckles)

685
00:42:23,340 --> 00:42:26,173
- Do you mind?
- No no no.

686
00:42:26,210 --> 00:42:28,178
Excuse me.

687
00:42:31,048 --> 00:42:33,039
- How are you?
- I'm fine.

688
00:42:33,083 --> 00:42:35,074
You ran.

689
00:42:35,119 --> 00:42:39,180
Well, I wish you'd been on the car
four cars down.

690
00:42:40,190 --> 00:42:43,819
So...

691
00:42:43,861 --> 00:42:47,661
- You okay?
- Yes, I'm fine.

692
00:42:47,698 --> 00:42:51,964
- Where we going?
- Um, Paddington.

693
00:42:52,002 --> 00:42:53,333
Oh.

694
00:43:01,345 --> 00:43:03,472
So, here's the taxi rank.

695
00:43:03,514 --> 00:43:06,915
I suppose it's bye-bye again.

696
00:43:06,951 --> 00:43:08,316
Oh.
(chuckles)

697
00:43:08,352 --> 00:43:11,082
They'll take you to wherever
you want to go... any hotel.

698
00:43:11,121 --> 00:43:14,249
You mean instead of me
walking you to your class?

699
00:43:16,594 --> 00:43:18,960
Carry your books.
I'll throw that in.

700
00:43:22,266 --> 00:43:23,699
Sure.

701
00:43:24,702 --> 00:43:26,192
Is that a "yes"?

702
00:43:26,236 --> 00:43:27,931
Yes.

703
00:43:27,972 --> 00:43:29,234
Why not?

704
00:43:30,541 --> 00:43:33,169
In which case, we um...
we have to go...

705
00:43:33,210 --> 00:43:34,734
we have to go back this way.

706
00:43:34,778 --> 00:43:37,372
You mind
if I just drop these off?

707
00:43:37,414 --> 00:43:39,348
Sure.

708
00:43:56,967 --> 00:43:58,867
(laughs)

709
00:44:05,709 --> 00:44:09,645
It's like " Yours is a glorious country,
Honeychurch!"

710
00:44:11,181 --> 00:44:13,672
Know that? Line from a book.
"Room with a View."

711
00:44:13,717 --> 00:44:15,708
Ah. E.M. Forster.

712
00:44:15,753 --> 00:44:17,721
- Mm-hmm. Have you read it?
- No.

713
00:44:17,755 --> 00:44:19,780
(laughs)

714
00:44:19,823 --> 00:44:22,621
- Do you think less of me?
- No no, not at all.

715
00:44:22,660 --> 00:44:25,458
It's just... I think
we're just very different.

716
00:44:25,496 --> 00:44:27,259
Probably.

717
00:44:27,297 --> 00:44:30,130
- Is that bad?
- No.

718
00:44:30,167 --> 00:44:32,294
I don't think so either.

719
00:44:32,336 --> 00:44:34,600
- (cellphone ringing)
- Hang on. Sorry.

720
00:44:35,839 --> 00:44:38,000
- Oh, sorry. I should get this.
- Go ahead.

721
00:44:38,042 --> 00:44:40,408
Hello, Mum? Hello.

722
00:44:40,444 --> 00:44:42,844
Sorry. I've been busy.

723
00:44:42,880 --> 00:44:44,643
Yeah.

724
00:44:44,682 --> 00:44:47,674
No. I'm out, actually.

725
00:44:47,718 --> 00:44:50,585
Yes yes, with someone.

726
00:44:50,621 --> 00:44:52,987
No, with someone else.

727
00:44:53,023 --> 00:44:55,253
Yes, a man.

728
00:44:58,262 --> 00:44:59,661
Oh, you did, did you?

729
00:45:02,499 --> 00:45:04,694
What,
an actual body?

730
00:45:07,938 --> 00:45:11,396
Okay, listen.

731
00:45:11,442 --> 00:45:13,410
Listen, I'll come
in early tomorrow morning,

732
00:45:13,444 --> 00:45:15,537
and we'll check it out together,
all right?

733
00:45:15,579 --> 00:45:17,945
All right. All right.

734
00:45:17,981 --> 00:45:20,108
Bye-bye. Bye.

735
00:45:20,150 --> 00:45:21,549
Yeah, I love you, too.
Bye. Bye.

736
00:45:21,585 --> 00:45:24,213
- Sorry. My mum.
- She worries about you?

737
00:45:24,254 --> 00:45:26,518
Mm-hmm.
Yeah.

738
00:45:26,557 --> 00:45:28,024
Well, about herself, actually.

739
00:45:28,058 --> 00:45:30,549
She's convinced
she's living next to Poland's answer to,

740
00:45:30,594 --> 00:45:33,290
- I don't know, Jack the Ripper.
- Oh.

741
00:45:33,330 --> 00:45:35,025
Do you live with her?

742
00:45:35,065 --> 00:45:37,090
Oh no. No no no.
God, no.

743
00:45:37,134 --> 00:45:39,295
- (laughs)
- Near, not with.

744
00:45:39,336 --> 00:45:41,361
She's all right.
She means well.

745
00:45:41,405 --> 00:45:43,839
She just had
a really rough ride of it is all.

746
00:45:43,874 --> 00:45:45,034
Why?

747
00:45:45,075 --> 00:45:49,307
Oh, well, my dad ran off to France
with his secretary,

748
00:45:49,346 --> 00:45:53,146
and then, about four years ago, she got
cancer, but she's completely recovered.

749
00:45:53,183 --> 00:45:54,980
She's fine.
She just doesn't want to admit it.

750
00:45:55,018 --> 00:45:56,212
You know.

751
00:45:56,253 --> 00:45:58,687
So...

752
00:45:58,722 --> 00:46:01,919
